

I_KISSSS_A_PC



---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Rule                                            | How to do it in real work with example                                                                                                                                                             |
| ----------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| I — Imagination is more powerful than knowledge | Before writing, imagine the failure scenario, not only the facts; example: “What happens if a bank app works but recovery fails during fraud?”                                                     |
| KI — Kindness                                   | Write to protect readers, not to scare them; example: say “audit your recovery path” instead of “your bank account is doomed.”                                                                     |
| S — Stupid: willing to be                       | Ask basic questions without ego; example: “What does this payment rail actually do for a normal investor?”                                                                                         |
| S — Steal like an artist                        | Study strong headlines, audit formats, checklists, and tables, then rebuild them in your own voice; example: turn a cybersecurity checklist into a wealth-protection audit.                        |
| S — Stamina                                     | Save creative energy for high-leverage work; example: write the hook, audit table, and bottom line first before polishing small sentences.                                                         |
| S — Smarter than me                             | Stay close to better thinkers, reports, engineers, regulators, and serious finance writers; example: read CFPB, FDIC, FIDO, NIST, banking reports, and expert commentary before finalizing claims. |
| A — Ask the chatbot first before any human      | Use chatbot as your first thinking partner, but never paste confidential banking data; example: “Give me 10 audit angles for SIM swap risk for U.S. investors.”                                    |
| P — Process, not product                        | Do not only admire the final article; study how it was built; example: hook → risk → data → audit table → checklist → sovereignty takeaway.                                                        |
| C — Curiosity                                   | Break everything into “What is it? How is it made? What can I borrow?”; example: study FedNow, then ask how speed changes fraud reaction time.                                                     |

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| 1% upgrade daily                                | Improve one tiny thing every day; example: today improve only headline clarity, tomorrow improve internal links, next day improve source quality.                                                  |
| 10/90 planning                                  | Spend 10% planning and 90% executing; example: 10 minutes outline the audit, then 90 minutes write the first draft.                                                                                |
| 80/20 Pareto principle                          | Find the 20% work that creates 80% reader value; example: focus on the audit checklist, not excessive background theory.                                                                           |
| GIGO — Garbage In, Garbage Out                  | Feed your brain and chatbot high-quality inputs; example: use regulator reports, real product pages, and clean prompts instead of vague “write me an article.”                                     |

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Auditor mindset                                 | Always ask, “Where can this fail?”; example: not “Is the app beautiful?” but “Can the user recover access under stress?”                                                                           |
| Writer mindset                                  | Turn technical risk into reader control; example: change “session hijacking” into “remove old trusted devices every month.”                                                                        |
